142
00:08:54.004 --> 00:08:57.964
The ETV6-RUNX1 fusion portends a favorable prognosis in childhood

143
00:08:58.064 --> 00:09:01.884
ALL, and this is work led by Tom MacLean, who was in Gary's lab, as well as

144
00:09:01.944 --> 00:09:04.563
Minyon Lo. And this has held up over time.

145
00:09:06.284 --> 00:09:10.224
So time marches on. Sorry.

146
00:09:10.864 --> 00:09:12.944
This is my favorite picture of Todd

147
00:09:13.744 --> 00:09:16.944
from back in '99. This was on the cover of one of these

148
00:09:16.984 --> 00:09:18.664
Dana-Farber magazines.

149
00:09:19.724 --> 00:09:23.294
But this study to me really, really heralded the

150
00:09:23.444 --> 00:09:26.724
start of the genomics revolution in cancer.

151
00:09:27.504 --> 00:09:30.784
And Todd was the first with Eric Lander to apply these DNA

152
00:09:30.844 --> 00:09:34.534
microarrays to the idea of doing expression profiling in cancer.

153
00:09:35.124 --> 00:09:39.074
And this just brought in this unbelievable omics era, as I like to call

154
00:09:39.124 --> 00:09:42.444
it, where we had this explosion of descriptive data.

155
00:09:42.504 --> 00:09:45.934
This warranted advances immediately in the field of computational

156
00:09:46.004 --> 00:09:48.904
biology to manage the analysis of this data.

157
00:09:48.914 --> 00:09:52.604
And important for the work that I've been doing, there was increasing access to

158
00:09:52.644 --> 00:09:56.204
small molecules and small molecule screening in the context of

159
00:09:56.213 --> 00:09:57.384
academic communities.

160
00:09:59.074 --> 00:10:02.804
And so this first publication that really, I think, marks the start of the

161
00:10:02.864 --> 00:10:06.024
genomics era in cancer was led by Todd

162
00:10:06.744 --> 00:10:10.304
really describing that, yes, we can use these DNA microarrays and

163
00:10:10.524 --> 00:10:14.444
expression signatures to classify disease, in this case, ALL versus

164
00:10:14.504 --> 00:10:18.404
AML. And then there were just a flurry of publications

165
00:10:18.444 --> 00:10:22.204
evaluating this technology, deploying it in work from Scott Armstrong to the

166
00:10:22.244 --> 00:10:26.164
identification of new gene expression classification with

167
00:10:26.264 --> 00:10:30.174
MLL, now called KMT2A, being unique from ALL and AML,

168
00:10:30.804 --> 00:10:33.663
the application to pharmacogenomics in very nice work out of St.

169
00:10:33.784 --> 00:10:37.244
Jude, as well as to outcome prediction in work from Europe.

170
00:10:38.764 --> 00:10:41.844
When I entered my postdoctoral training, which was with

171
00:10:42.764 --> 00:10:46.644
Todd, the project that I took on was to ask, could we

172
00:10:46.704 --> 00:10:50.564
now bring gene expression to small molecule discovery to chemical

173
00:10:50.584 --> 00:10:54.244
biology? And it was the idea that we could use gene expression signatures

174
00:10:54.644 --> 00:10:58.483
as surrogates for different biological states and then adapt those

175
00:10:58.524 --> 00:11:01.024
signatures to high-throughput screening assays.

176
00:11:03.104 --> 00:11:06.994
So we were able to build these assays and then deploy them to a number

177
00:11:07.044 --> 00:11:10.434
of different questions in the context of cancer,

178
00:11:10.884 --> 00:11:14.484
initially looking at differentiation, which led to our identification of

179
00:11:14.584 --> 00:11:18.284
SYK as a target in AML, and there were clinical trials where there were complete

180
00:11:18.364 --> 00:11:21.384
responses to SYK inhibitors, neuroblastoma

181
00:11:21.444 --> 00:11:25.064
differentiation, the idea of modulating transcription

182
00:11:25.164 --> 00:11:29.074
factor abnormalities and their transcriptional outputs, and a number

183
00:11:29.104 --> 00:11:30.994
of other projects, including, as Dr.

184
00:11:31.164 --> 00:11:35.124
Erwin said, the idea of now applying this more systematically

185
00:11:35.164 --> 00:11:38.844
in the context of the Connectivity Map or CMap led by Justin

186
00:11:38.904 --> 00:11:39.804
Lamb at the Broad.

187
00:11:42.404 --> 00:11:46.124
Technologies continue to evolve, and I think an important theme here is in our

188
00:11:46.144 --> 00:11:49.504
research programs, really staying up to speed with new

189
00:11:49.564 --> 00:11:52.204
technologies and deploying them to answer questions.

190
00:11:52.924 --> 00:11:56.834
One of my very strong memories is being in the audience at a meeting where

191
00:11:56.864 --> 00:12:00.804
this first sequencing of an AML genome was presented, and this was work

192
00:12:00.824 --> 00:12:04.534
led by Tim Ley and Elaine Mardis with senior authorship from

193
00:12:04.544 --> 00:12:08.404
Richard Wilson. This again really brought us into a new era

194
00:12:08.444 --> 00:12:12.360
in what we could do in cancer.And so I call this the days

195
00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:13.660
of landscape genomics.

196
00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:18.890
And so I had the privilege of working with Mignonne Lowe and the Broad on

197
00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:23.140
sequencing the genomic landscape of JMML in a project led by Elliot

198
00:12:23.180 --> 00:12:24.000
Daus-Sieglebs.

199
00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:29.020
And this again had prognostic importance in that we

200
00:12:29.060 --> 00:12:33.040
discovered that in children whose JMML had two or more alterations, this

201
00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:35.320
portended a particularly poor prognosis.

202
00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:41.680
As you heard from Meredith, our lab has worked on Ewing sarcoma since the

203
00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:45.700
kind of tail end of my post-doctoral training in Todd Golub's lab.

204
00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:49.320
And I just want to give a little brief background because I'm going to talk about a

205
00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:52.500
few Ewing sarcoma vignettes across this presentation.

206
00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:57.160
So Ewing is the second most common tumor that involves bone in pediatric

207
00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:01.100
patients. And curates for children with localized disease have improved

208
00:13:01.540 --> 00:13:05.050
through the incorporation of additional chemotherapy agents and

209
00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:06.800
interval-compressed chemotherapy.

210
00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:10.940
But our curates for patients with metastatic disease remain very poor.

211
00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:15.180
Nothing that we've done in decades has improved their outcome, and relapse is

212
00:13:15.219 --> 00:13:16.120
nearly always fatal.

213
00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:19.800
Many ways I say this is a canonical pediatric cancer.

214
00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:22.100
It's driven by a fusion oncoprotein.

215
00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:25.640
These are EWS-ETS fusions, most typically

216
00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:29.380
EWS-FLI1. EWS is an RNA-binding protein, but the

217
00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:33.120
RNA-binding domain is not retained in the fusion, but intrinsically disordered

218
00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:33.760
regions are.

219
00:13:34.580 --> 00:13:37.200
And then FLI1 is another ETS transcription factor.

220
00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:41.690
And these fusions are observed in EWS-FLI in about 80 to 90%,

221
00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:44.880
and then there are a smattering of other fusions in this class.

222
00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:49.080
Cell of origin is still debated. There are camps that say mesenchymal, neural

223
00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:52.200
crest. It's possible that it could originate in either.

224
00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:57.160
So work from many people over the years, Steve Leznick,

225
00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:02.060
Miguel Rivera, Sigal Kadosh, Ian Davis, Heinrich Kovar, some work

226
00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:05.870
from our lab, and many others, I should say, has taught us that

227
00:14:05.920 --> 00:14:09.210
this fusion acts as a pioneer transcription factor, and it's really quite

228
00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:13.210
interesting. It establishes de novo enhancers at

229
00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:17.250
GGAA microsatellite repeats, where it acts as a transcriptional

230
00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:21.200
activator, and it recruits the BAF complex to these GGAA repeats.

231
00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:25.960
It's also been reported to compete with typical ETS to repress

232
00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:29.780
gene expression, although that function of the fusion has been less deeply

233
00:14:29.790 --> 00:14:30.260
studied.

234
00:14:32.550 --> 00:14:36.329
And so we also had the privilege of being engaged in

235
00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:38.700
sequencing Ewing sarcoma tumors.

236
00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:42.080
This is work that was led by Brian Crompton when he trained in my lab, and Brian

237
00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:45.440
now leads a lab at Dana-Farber focused on liquid biopsy.

238
00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:50.680
We had the pleasure of collaborating in this work with Gaddy Getz's team, as

239
00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:51.940
well as with John Marmura.

240
00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:56.520
And what emerged from this sequencing effort is this finding that

241
00:14:56.600 --> 00:15:00.510
recurrent mutations are really very few in pediatric cancers, and this was one

242
00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:04.520
of the earlier studies to do that. We had two other

243
00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:08.310
groups that were similarly engaged in sequencing efforts around that same time from

244
00:15:08.310 --> 00:15:11.700
Mike Dyer and Olivier Delattre, as well as Javed Khan.

245
00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:15.350
And it was very reassuring to see that all three groups really came to very similar

246
00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:16.050
conclusions.

247
00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:21.480
So these, as we said, these somatic mutations are

248
00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:25.320
relatively low disease burden or quiet genomes across many

249
00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:29.260
childhood cancers. In fact, most, as shown here, compared to adult.

250
00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:33.200
And I think as we know now, we see structural abnormalities in childhood

251
00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:36.420
cancers more than many somatic mutations.

252
00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:42.540
Another finding from this work was that there were recurrent mutations in the

253
00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:46.160
gene STAG2. And again, this was seen across all three of the studies.

254
00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:50.920
So STAG2 is a member of the cohesin complex, which has a number of

255
00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:54.120
functions in the cell, including gene regulation.

256
00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:58.340
And these mutations tend to lead to an absence of the STAG2 protein.

257
00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:04.340
So once again, this is an example where the genomic

258
00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:08.400
sequencing has clinical impact through its bearing

259
00:16:08.420 --> 00:16:12.199
as a prognostic marker. And so multiple groups now, including as

260
00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:16.040
shown here, Dave Shulman, in a study led out of Brian Crompton's

261
00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:19.960
lab, and also Riaz Gillani and a number of authors, have

262
00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:23.880
shown again and again that these mutations are a poor prognostic feature.

263
00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:27.320
And this will really be the first genomic

264
00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:31.400
biomarker of poor outcome in Ewing sarcoma, so really important.

265
00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:36.980
So we made an observation in our initial sequencing

266
00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:40.880
study that the patients who had tumors that had an absence of

267
00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:44.880
STAG2 protein had a higher incidence of metastatic disease, and we

268
00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:47.400
aim to study that further in the lab.

269
00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:53.160
So Biniam Madani, another very talented trainee who worked with us, who is

270
00:16:53.220 --> 00:16:56.840
now at BMS, and Gabriela Alexe, who is a very senior

271
00:16:57.300 --> 00:17:00.890
and outstanding data scientist in the lab, worked on this study together.

272
00:17:01.660 --> 00:17:05.480
And so Biniam generated a series of isogenic models where he knocked out

273
00:17:05.600 --> 00:17:09.260
STAG2 to mimic the impact of the mutations and was able to

274
00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:12.220
demonstrate that this promoted metastatic disease.

275
00:17:12.681 --> 00:17:16.100
And at the same time as we published this work, Didier Surdez in

276
00:17:16.360 --> 00:17:20.060
Olivier Delattre's lab published very similar findings that the loss of

277
00:17:20.080 --> 00:17:23.600
STAG2 was associated with migratory and invasive

278
00:17:23.661 --> 00:17:24.120
behavior.

279
00:17:25.641 --> 00:17:29.540
And so we also began to probe, well, what might the mechanisms be behind

280
00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:33.160
this observation? And so we looked at RNA sequencing after

281
00:17:33.220 --> 00:17:36.140
knocking out STAG2 in Ewing sarcoma cell line models.

282
00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:40.140
And then we also looked at data from a number of different primary tumor

283
00:17:40.200 --> 00:17:44.100
studies. And again and again, what we saw is that the absence of STAG2

284
00:17:44.110 --> 00:17:47.760
was actually associated with a repression of parts of the EPHLIP

285
00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:48.300
signature.

286
00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:53.020
And this was in part due to alterations in 3D chromatin.

287
00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:56.760
And again, Olivier's lab found very similar findings in their

288
00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:57.160
study.

289
00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:02.180
And so this was exciting to us because there was an emerging literature from a

290
00:18:02.260 --> 00:18:05.600
number of different laboratories that the dosage of EPHLIP matters.

291
00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:07.480
It matters in terms of the cell state.

292
00:18:08.120 --> 00:18:11.710
And one of the findings across a number of groups that was quite consistent with

293
00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:15.700
what we were observing in these primary tumors related to STAG2

294
00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:19.700
is that when you lower EPHLIP levels, not shut it off completely, but lower

295
00:18:19.740 --> 00:18:23.280
it, that tends to be associated with more mesenchymal-like

296
00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:24.880
migratory invasive

297
00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:29.696
behavior.So

298
00:18:29.706 --> 00:18:33.256
time continues to march on. We went from sort of landscape

299
00:18:33.336 --> 00:18:35.506
genomics, then to functional genomics.

300
00:18:35.536 --> 00:18:38.956
And I'm borrowing this analogy from Bill Hahn, who likes cars,

301
00:18:39.896 --> 00:18:43.696
and says, "You can identify the parts of a car and

302
00:18:43.776 --> 00:18:47.536
name them, but do we know how they work?" And technologies such as RNAi and

303
00:18:47.556 --> 00:18:51.396
CRISPR really allowed us to go from characterizing landscapes to

304
00:18:51.456 --> 00:18:54.056
now functionalizing on a genome scale.

305
00:18:55.956 --> 00:18:59.476
And so we were very fortunate to be involved in the

306
00:18:59.486 --> 00:19:01.676
dependency map work at the Broad Institute.

307
00:19:01.756 --> 00:19:05.296
It was really very exciting to me that this year the AACR Team Science

308
00:19:05.396 --> 00:19:09.296
Award was to the DepMap team led now by Paquita Vazquez.

309
00:19:09.326 --> 00:19:13.246
And so our work in PDET really built upon this much larger

310
00:19:13.336 --> 00:19:17.166
work around dependency map that was led by Bill Hahn and David Root and

311
00:19:17.236 --> 00:19:21.076
others in the early days. So I think it's an idea familiar to most people in the

312
00:19:21.136 --> 00:19:23.716
audience that we can take cancer models.

313
00:19:23.836 --> 00:19:27.496
Primarily, this has been done with cancer cell lines, and profile their genetic

314
00:19:27.556 --> 00:19:31.026
molecular features and then perturb them systematically with

315
00:19:31.116 --> 00:19:34.986
RNAi or CRISPR or small molecules, build computational

316
00:19:35.016 --> 00:19:38.336
pipelines, and then use that type of data to either nominate therapeutic

317
00:19:38.356 --> 00:19:42.216
hypotheses or it's actually informing us quite a bit about

318
00:19:42.256 --> 00:19:44.556
the underlying mechanisms of these cancers.

319
00:19:45.206 --> 00:19:48.976
And so now over 10 years ago, we had the opportunity to really build

320
00:19:49.096 --> 00:19:53.016
out the pediatric component of this together with Paquita Vazquez and also

321
00:19:53.076 --> 00:19:56.396
Charlie Roberts at the time when he was at Dana-Farber.

322
00:19:58.736 --> 00:20:02.416
And just very briefly, I'm going to focus first on the CRISPR element of this data.

323
00:20:03.016 --> 00:20:06.576
These are genome-scale screens. They use two to four

324
00:20:06.676 --> 00:20:10.496
guides per gene, depending on the library, and over 1,000 cancer

325
00:20:10.556 --> 00:20:12.056
cell line models have been screened.

326
00:20:12.636 --> 00:20:16.516
And I think very importantly, the data's made public before there's actually a

327
00:20:16.596 --> 00:20:20.256
new publication. And so this is really a living data set that continues to get

328
00:20:20.296 --> 00:20:21.996
updated as more models are screened.

329
00:20:23.036 --> 00:20:26.216
And these screens are generally done at a 21-day time point.

330
00:20:26.256 --> 00:20:30.096
And we've been most interested in guides like this that drop out, as they

331
00:20:30.136 --> 00:20:33.906
might represent a gene that when deleted, has a deleterious effect on those

332
00:20:33.936 --> 00:20:37.566
cancer cells. I think it's important to also mention there are other groups that

333
00:20:37.596 --> 00:20:40.906
have been engaged in DepMap-like work, including the Sanger, as well as a really

334
00:20:40.916 --> 00:20:44.336
nice effort in Australia led by Ron Firestein.

335
00:20:46.376 --> 00:20:50.085
So one of our first tasks when we built this first data set, which included a

336
00:20:50.136 --> 00:20:52.506
little over 80 pediatric cancer models,

337
00:20:53.456 --> 00:20:55.236
was to ask some fundamental questions.

338
00:20:55.256 --> 00:20:58.436
First, some people would ask us, "Well, pediatric cancers, they don't have that

339
00:20:58.496 --> 00:21:01.756
many mutations. Maybe they actually don't have that many

340
00:21:01.776 --> 00:21:04.476
dependencies." And that turned out not to be true.

341
00:21:04.576 --> 00:21:08.456
So pediatric cancers have as many dependencies as adult cancers.

342
00:21:09.196 --> 00:21:12.606
And this first build of this project was led on a

343
00:21:12.636 --> 00:21:15.996
computational side by Nikesh Dharia, a really talented pediatric

344
00:21:16.036 --> 00:21:19.956
oncologist, cross-trained in computational biology as well as Lily

345
00:21:19.976 --> 00:21:22.996
Guenther, another really talented pediatric oncologist.

346
00:21:23.036 --> 00:21:26.696
And so Nikesh is now at Genentech, and Lily is running her own

347
00:21:26.756 --> 00:21:30.256
lab at St. Jude. And Lily led this effort on the biology

348
00:21:30.356 --> 00:21:30.756
side.

349
00:21:32.696 --> 00:21:36.636
And so another finding from this work is that many pediatric

350
00:21:36.696 --> 00:21:40.116
cancers, although I'll show you not all, have a very

351
00:21:40.216 --> 00:21:43.896
striking dependence retained on lineage-related

352
00:21:43.976 --> 00:21:47.376
transcription factors. And these are, in fact, often the top

353
00:21:47.456 --> 00:21:51.205
dependencies that are selective in that childhood cancer compared to all the other

354
00:21:51.236 --> 00:21:55.136
cancers that have been screened. And this is very strikingly the

355
00:21:55.216 --> 00:21:56.496
case for neuroblastoma.

356
00:21:57.356 --> 00:22:00.645
In work that we collaborated on with Tom Look's lab as well as

357
00:22:00.656 --> 00:22:04.546
Rick Young's lab that was led by Adam Durbin, Nikesh Dharia, as well as

358
00:22:04.576 --> 00:22:08.336
Mark Zimmerman, really showed that in neuroblastoma,

359
00:22:08.516 --> 00:22:12.276
these transcription factors form what's called a coregulatory circuit,

360
00:22:12.416 --> 00:22:15.976
where they self-regulate, they're marked by super enhancers, they're highly

361
00:22:15.986 --> 00:22:18.036
expressed, and then they regulate one another.

362
00:22:18.666 --> 00:22:22.556
And now that we had the DepMap data, we were able to show for the first time that

363
00:22:22.596 --> 00:22:26.176
these coregulatory transcription factors are also really strong

364
00:22:26.196 --> 00:22:27.676
dependencies in this disease.

365
00:22:28.656 --> 00:22:31.446
I also want to acknowledge there were two other really beautiful papers that

366
00:22:31.476 --> 00:22:35.236
preceded ours that also contributed to defining this idea of

367
00:22:35.276 --> 00:22:38.936
coregulatory circuitry in neuroblastoma and looked at both an adrenergic

368
00:22:39.076 --> 00:22:42.756
state, which is shown here in this image, but also a more

369
00:22:42.796 --> 00:22:46.596
mesenchymal state. And so this idea that there's heterogeneity in

370
00:22:46.776 --> 00:22:50.136
state in neuroblastoma as well as other cancers is another major

371
00:22:50.175 --> 00:22:52.196
theme that has emerged over the years.

372
00:22:54.016 --> 00:22:57.396
So these are hard to drug. So these are hard to make small molecule

373
00:22:57.696 --> 00:23:01.596
targeted therapies against. But this work, I think, is still important even

374
00:23:01.636 --> 00:23:04.116
while we try to make drugs against them for other reasons.

375
00:23:04.146 --> 00:23:07.576
And so this is a really amazing study from Mark

376
00:23:07.616 --> 00:23:11.186
Yermakovich in John Marras's lab that looked at the

377
00:23:11.256 --> 00:23:14.796
targeting of intracellular oncoproteins with peptide-centric

378
00:23:14.836 --> 00:23:18.236
CARs. And so one of the targets that they focused on was

379
00:23:18.276 --> 00:23:21.836
FOX2B, which was the same target I showed you as part of a coregulatory

380
00:23:21.896 --> 00:23:24.756
circuit and a strong dependency in neuroblastoma.

381
00:23:25.346 --> 00:23:29.186
And to me, this is really a perfect target and that the cells require this target

382
00:23:29.196 --> 00:23:32.836
for ongoing proliferation. And so now we can even use data like

383
00:23:32.876 --> 00:23:35.816
DepMap to intersect that with data looking at

384
00:23:36.316 --> 00:23:39.656
peptide-centric CAR technology, cell surface technology, et cetera.

385
00:23:41.476 --> 00:23:44.476
I also want to mention that this idea of state

386
00:23:44.936 --> 00:23:48.356
heterogeneity is really important, we think, in terms of

387
00:23:48.396 --> 00:23:52.156
response to therapy, whether it be immunotherapy or small molecule

388
00:23:52.196 --> 00:23:56.176
therapy. And this was work that Nathaniel Mabe led out of my lab in a

389
00:23:56.236 --> 00:23:59.696
very close collaboration with Robbie Masner's lab, and Min Huang was

390
00:24:00.596 --> 00:24:01.906
Nathaniel's partner in this work.

391
00:24:02.616 --> 00:24:06.516
That showed that in the adrenergic state of neuroblastoma, these cells have higher

392
00:24:06.616 --> 00:24:09.876
levels of GD2 and tend to be more responsive to

393
00:24:09.936 --> 00:24:13.516
GD2-directed therapy. But in the mesenchymal state, GD2

394
00:24:13.596 --> 00:24:14.646
levels are lower.

395
00:24:16.656 --> 00:24:20.576
And then in work from a number of years ago by Mandy Babone Iniguez

396
00:24:20.586 --> 00:24:24.206
showing that, yes, state also matters, and you can see

397
00:24:24.206 --> 00:24:27.696
enhancer rewiring and this state switch in the context of

398
00:24:28.236 --> 00:24:29.956
small molecule targeted therapies as well.

399
00:24:30.016 --> 00:24:33.076
So again, I think this is a very important theme as we think about drug

400
00:24:33.116 --> 00:24:36.716
resistance.So we were

401
00:24:36.956 --> 00:24:40.636
really optimistic when we started this project and we had the neuroblastoma

402
00:24:40.676 --> 00:24:44.476
data, and we saw this observation in things like AML and rhabdo that

403
00:24:44.516 --> 00:24:48.116
these tumors retain dependency on core regulatory circuitry

404
00:24:48.556 --> 00:24:52.376
that we might use this type of data to identify the cell of origin of

405
00:24:52.416 --> 00:24:55.836
Ewing sarcoma. And I will say that turned out to be an utter failure.

406
00:24:55.996 --> 00:24:59.816
We did not see that at all . And in fact, what we saw was something quite

407
00:24:59.876 --> 00:25:03.556
different. So these tumors certainly depend on the fusion,

408
00:25:04.096 --> 00:25:07.976
as guides directed against FLI and EWS-R1 score very strongly.

409
00:25:07.996 --> 00:25:10.486
There's also a very strong paralog relationship.

410
00:25:10.516 --> 00:25:14.365
When you lose STAG2, you're dependent on STAG1.

411
00:25:14.376 --> 00:25:16.756
And then we found two other targets that I'll discuss.

412
00:25:16.856 --> 00:25:20.846
But what you don't see are highly expressed activating

413
00:25:20.936 --> 00:25:22.896
transcription factors that mark lineage.

414
00:25:24.216 --> 00:25:27.996
And I was really excited when Didier Surdace actually published this paper that

415
00:25:28.236 --> 00:25:30.716
really speaks to this in a more formal way.

416
00:25:31.036 --> 00:25:32.956
And I love the use of the word hegemonic.

417
00:25:33.396 --> 00:25:37.386
So the hegemonic EWS-R1/ETS oncoprotein overrules

418
00:25:37.456 --> 00:25:39.816
core regulatory circuitry principles in Ewing sarcoma.

419
00:25:39.856 --> 00:25:41.896
And we absolutely agree with this.

420
00:25:42.376 --> 00:25:45.056
And I just love the title, so I wanted to share it.

421
00:25:45.076 --> 00:25:48.556
And I think for those of you who've worked on Ewing for a long time, this tumor

422
00:25:48.636 --> 00:25:50.536
just doesn't follow the rules, I'm going to say.

423
00:25:52.336 --> 00:25:55.916
So what we saw instead was this extremely strong Goldilocks

424
00:25:55.956 --> 00:25:59.396
phenomena in Ewing, where the tumors depend on a very

425
00:25:59.516 --> 00:26:03.096
precise level of the fusion. If you fully repress it, it's very

426
00:26:03.116 --> 00:26:07.096
deleterious. If you overexpress it or manipulate it in other ways, that is

427
00:26:07.156 --> 00:26:11.036
also equally deleterious. And while we've focused on this in Ewing, this is

428
00:26:11.136 --> 00:26:14.756
clearly emerging as a theme across other oncogene signaling

429
00:26:14.856 --> 00:26:18.836
pathways, and there's a community that's growing around this concept.

430
00:26:20.296 --> 00:26:23.736
And so one of the first targets that we focused on was TRIM8,

431
00:26:24.336 --> 00:26:27.976
and obviously it's scoring very strongly in the dependency map screening.

432
00:26:28.776 --> 00:26:32.636
It also scored as a top hit in a flow-based screen that we did

433
00:26:32.696 --> 00:26:36.276
using a reporter model reporting out on EWS-FLI levels.

434
00:26:36.816 --> 00:26:40.076
So in this screen, the loss of TRIM8 was predicted to increase

435
00:26:40.156 --> 00:26:41.256
EWS-FLI levels.

436
00:26:43.156 --> 00:26:46.916
And so what is TRIM8? TRIM8 is an E3 ligase.

437
00:26:47.016 --> 00:26:50.876
It has a ring domain. And I think when we think about this target

438
00:26:50.916 --> 00:26:54.086
from a therapeutic window, importantly, the TRIM8 knockout mouse was

439
00:26:54.096 --> 00:26:58.016
viable, and TRIM8 in the first build of the data only scored

440
00:26:58.136 --> 00:27:01.436
in Ewing sarcoma. It didn't score in any other disease, suggesting, again,

441
00:27:02.076 --> 00:27:06.006
really selective dependency. So this work was led by Alex Song,

442
00:27:06.056 --> 00:27:10.016
again, really talented trainee who worked with us, and Alex is now

443
00:27:10.036 --> 00:27:10.696
at AstraZeneca.

444
00:27:12.236 --> 00:27:16.096
And so what Alex went on to show both in vitro and in vivo is that knockout

445
00:27:16.105 --> 00:27:17.956
of TRIM8 had a very strong phenotype.

446
00:27:18.066 --> 00:27:20.196
This is showing some data from an in vivo model.

447
00:27:21.736 --> 00:27:24.175
And indeed did regulate EWS-FLI levels.

448
00:27:24.236 --> 00:27:27.976
And so when he knocked out TRIM8, EWS-FLI goes up.

449
00:27:28.156 --> 00:27:31.236
We saw this across every model that we evaluated with the fusion.

450
00:27:32.136 --> 00:27:35.355
NKX2-2 goes up. That's a direct target of the fusion.

451
00:27:35.956 --> 00:27:39.916
And importantly, wild-type EWS doesn't change, and as shown in the

452
00:27:39.976 --> 00:27:42.116
other figure, wild-type FLI does not change.

453
00:27:42.156 --> 00:27:45.966
So we think this effect is specific to the fusion and not the wild-type

454
00:27:45.996 --> 00:27:46.596
counterparts.

455
00:27:48.466 --> 00:27:51.416
And so in the interest of time, I'm just going to show you one more figure panel on

456
00:27:51.456 --> 00:27:55.346
this target. We also did a series of experiments to look at

457
00:27:55.376 --> 00:27:58.876
what overexpression does to these cells, and this is a very simple one where we

458
00:27:58.916 --> 00:28:02.176
just used a dox-inducible system to overexpress the fusion.

459
00:28:02.676 --> 00:28:06.636
And consistently, this was deleterious, inducing annexin-positive cell

460
00:28:06.696 --> 00:28:09.796
death. And this wasn't just an in vitro artifact.

461
00:28:10.276 --> 00:28:13.825
When we overexpress the fusion, including in patient-derived xenograft

462
00:28:13.896 --> 00:28:17.336
models, it's similarly very deleterious in vivo.

463
00:28:19.656 --> 00:28:23.376
So we also identified a second target that spoke to this

464
00:28:23.576 --> 00:28:26.956
Goldilocks phenomenon. This is work that Diana Lu led from the lab.

465
00:28:27.036 --> 00:28:30.186
Diana did her MD-PhD studies with us, again, another

466
00:28:30.196 --> 00:28:31.996
extremely talented trainee.

467
00:28:32.816 --> 00:28:36.436
And so Diana got interested in ETV6, and I was, of course,

468
00:28:36.636 --> 00:28:40.126
excited about this target because this is the first gene that I actually worked on

469
00:28:40.796 --> 00:28:41.836
as a medical student.

470
00:28:42.796 --> 00:28:46.756
And so ETV6, as I said, is a master developmental transcription factor.

471
00:28:47.176 --> 00:28:50.856
It's a repressor in hematopoiesis, and it is recurrently

472
00:28:50.916 --> 00:28:54.496
mutated in hematologic malignancies, as I showed you in the

473
00:28:54.536 --> 00:28:58.516
ETV6-RUNX1 case, but also in other heme malignancies

474
00:28:58.536 --> 00:29:01.776
and beyond heme malignancies. And it has a

475
00:29:02.376 --> 00:29:05.996
DNA-binding domain that binds to GGAA motifs.

476
00:29:08.356 --> 00:29:12.076
And so Diana went on to show that the knockout of ETV6

477
00:29:12.196 --> 00:29:15.916
inhibits Ewing sarcoma growth, colony formation, and tumor

478
00:29:16.356 --> 00:29:20.136
progression in vitro and in vivo, using both CRISPR knockout

479
00:29:20.236 --> 00:29:22.196
systems as well as dTAG systems.

480
00:29:24.176 --> 00:29:28.006
And she also showed that in Ewing, as observed in hematopoiesis,

481
00:29:28.216 --> 00:29:30.916
ETV6 is a transcriptional repressor.

482
00:29:30.976 --> 00:29:34.916
So here she used a dTAG system so she could acutely degrade ETV6

483
00:29:34.936 --> 00:29:38.886
and then ask what happens to gene expression, and gene expression indeed

484
00:29:38.936 --> 00:29:39.456
goes up.

485
00:29:40.336 --> 00:29:44.236
And the programs were quite consistent across multiple Ewing sarcoma

486
00:29:44.296 --> 00:29:44.696
models.

487
00:29:46.756 --> 00:29:50.416
So what she observed in this context is that when we looked at gene

488
00:29:50.436 --> 00:29:54.076
pathways, EWS-FLI signatures were now going up very

489
00:29:54.156 --> 00:29:54.536
strongly.

490
00:29:56.116 --> 00:29:59.436
And so this felt, again, to us like another Goldilocks phenomenology.

491
00:29:59.486 --> 00:30:03.216
And so she hypothesized that because ETV6 is an S

492
00:30:03.296 --> 00:30:06.836
transcription factor, FLI is an S transcription factor, that

493
00:30:06.876 --> 00:30:10.636
perhaps the fusion and ETV6 were found at similar sites on chromatin.

494
00:30:11.356 --> 00:30:15.316
And that's, in fact, what she found, that ETV6 colocalizes

495
00:30:15.376 --> 00:30:18.796
with FLI on chromatin, and when you now remove

496
00:30:18.916 --> 00:30:22.156
ETV6, you degrade it, you get an excess of

497
00:30:22.176 --> 00:30:26.096
EWS-FLI on chromatin. And she went on to show even that she could rescue

498
00:30:26.136 --> 00:30:29.096
this phenomenology by knocking out individual

499
00:30:29.196 --> 00:30:32.788
genes.And so we were pretty

500
00:30:32.828 --> 00:30:36.808
excited when Chris Vakoc called us up to ask what did we think of

501
00:30:36.828 --> 00:30:40.628
ETV6 in Ewing sarcoma, and we were like, "Well, Chris, what do you think about it?"

502
00:30:40.648 --> 00:30:44.468
And so he had very similar data, and so we were pretty

503
00:30:44.488 --> 00:30:47.568
excited. I always like when other labs are working on the same thing because it

504
00:30:47.628 --> 00:30:50.048
means that you're probably onto something that's very robust.

505
00:30:50.738 --> 00:30:54.408
And so we both published together, in "Nature Cell Biology," and Beth

506
00:30:54.448 --> 00:30:58.368
Lawler, with April Affelbaum training in her lab, wrote this really lovely on

507
00:30:58.388 --> 00:31:02.188
"News and Views" that I think summarizes this quite nicely, that the

508
00:31:02.248 --> 00:31:05.247
fusion and ETV6 actually are competing on chromonin.

509
00:31:05.288 --> 00:31:09.208
ETV6 is constraining how much Ephi is found on chromonin,

510
00:31:09.808 --> 00:31:12.908
and when you remove ETV6, you get excess Ephi on chromonin,

511
00:31:13.578 --> 00:31:15.348
that's deleterious to Ewing cells.

512
00:31:15.368 --> 00:31:19.168
And Chris also focused on a differentiation phenotype in that context.

513
00:31:21.368 --> 00:31:24.978
So I'd like to mention some of the other types of dependencies that we and

514
00:31:25.048 --> 00:31:27.848
others have identified in the context of DepMap.

515
00:31:28.408 --> 00:31:31.968
And one that I think is actually particularly of interest in pediatric

516
00:31:32.028 --> 00:31:34.658
cancers are paralog relationships.

517
00:31:34.728 --> 00:31:38.708
And this is the idea that you have two paralogous genes, and when

518
00:31:38.768 --> 00:31:42.428
one is lost or repressed, cells can acquire exquisite

519
00:31:42.488 --> 00:31:43.688
dependency on the other.

520
00:31:45.628 --> 00:31:49.548
And one of the earliest papers that I saw on this in specific targets

521
00:31:49.628 --> 00:31:53.608
in childhood cancers was actually from Charlie Roberts' lab, demonstrating that

522
00:31:53.748 --> 00:31:57.738
ARID1B is a specific vulnerability in ARID1A mutant

523
00:31:57.848 --> 00:32:01.638
cancers. And this is now held up across multiple other studies.

524
00:32:03.068 --> 00:32:06.748
Many groups now have shown that this STAG1, STAG2

525
00:32:06.808 --> 00:32:10.688
paralog relationship is really quite strong, and I think these are all quite good

526
00:32:10.748 --> 00:32:12.408
targets for these childhood cancers.

527
00:32:13.588 --> 00:32:16.888
Really lovely work from Claire Malone, who trained in my lab.

528
00:32:17.948 --> 00:32:21.588
Claire's now at InduPro and leading a clinical trial, which I think is really

529
00:32:21.608 --> 00:32:23.668
exciting about her company. It's very exciting.

530
00:32:24.668 --> 00:32:28.068
Claire worked on NXT1 and showed that NXT1 is a

531
00:32:28.148 --> 00:32:32.138
paralog with NXT2, and that these neuroblastoma cells and

532
00:32:32.168 --> 00:32:35.928
other cancers that have profound repression of NXT2 are very

533
00:32:35.988 --> 00:32:39.878
strongly dependent on NXT1. And again, I think this is a really

534
00:32:39.888 --> 00:32:43.628
exciting target. And then finally, VRK1.

535
00:32:44.448 --> 00:32:47.168
Our group published this with Bill Hahn and Mariella Filbin.

536
00:32:47.508 --> 00:32:50.228
There are other independent groups focused on this target.

537
00:32:50.288 --> 00:32:53.848
VRK1 is a synthetic lethal target in VRK2 promoter

538
00:32:53.948 --> 00:32:57.468
methylated cancers of the nervous system, including brain tumor

539
00:32:57.568 --> 00:33:00.087
subsets, and neuroblastoma.

540
00:33:01.968 --> 00:33:05.948
And so with sort of this early phase of pediatric DepMap and proof

541
00:33:05.988 --> 00:33:09.828
of concept demonstrating the importance, we were super excited to be

542
00:33:09.868 --> 00:33:13.848
able to take this to a new level in a collaboration across the Broad

543
00:33:13.908 --> 00:33:16.648
Institute led by Paquita Vazquez, St.

544
00:33:16.748 --> 00:33:20.708
Jude, led by Charlie Roberts, and our team at Dana-Farber, and many, many

545
00:33:20.748 --> 00:33:23.588
investigators making critical contributions to this.

546
00:33:23.628 --> 00:33:26.868
This has really been, to me, an amazing collaborative effort.

547
00:33:27.748 --> 00:33:31.548
One of our goals has been to try to expand screening into

548
00:33:31.568 --> 00:33:34.928
models that we were unable to screen before, and this has been a huge success of

549
00:33:34.968 --> 00:33:36.628
this project over the last few years.

550
00:33:37.228 --> 00:33:40.348
We've more than tripled the number of childhood cancer models that were screened.

551
00:33:40.408 --> 00:33:44.388
We've been able to screen in hemolignancy models not screenable before, as

552
00:33:44.428 --> 00:33:48.328
well as in a number of brain tumor models, including DMG as

553
00:33:48.408 --> 00:33:49.098
one example.

554
00:33:51.468 --> 00:33:54.848
So I want to end this last part talking about

555
00:33:54.928 --> 00:33:58.748
therapeutics and the challenges and some of the directions that we're

556
00:33:58.808 --> 00:34:01.588
taking on therapeutic work in our own lab.

557
00:34:02.388 --> 00:34:06.028
So I think we would all agree there are many challenges involved in

558
00:34:06.068 --> 00:34:08.488
developing therapies in pediatric oncology.

559
00:34:08.988 --> 00:34:12.748
Just to mention a few, these transcription factors are

560
00:34:12.888 --> 00:34:16.649
such important drivers, and they make for very challenging drug targets.

561
00:34:17.448 --> 00:34:21.348
These diseases have a low mutational burden, so generally, they've not

562
00:34:21.408 --> 00:34:23.748
been responsive to immune checkpoint inhibitors.

563
00:34:24.649 --> 00:34:28.149
These are rare and ultra-rare cancers, so there's a lack of market

564
00:34:28.208 --> 00:34:32.089
incentive for developing drugs. And it's been estimated that about

565
00:34:32.188 --> 00:34:35.879
half of pediatric cancer drivers are unique to pediatric cancers,

566
00:34:36.609 --> 00:34:38.448
so there's no market incentive for this.

567
00:34:38.708 --> 00:34:42.448
So what are some of the tactics that we and others have been taking?

568
00:34:42.788 --> 00:34:43.078
One was,

569
00:34:43.928 --> 00:34:45.228
is there low-hanging fruit, right?

570
00:34:45.268 --> 00:34:49.257
And so this was a project led by Yana Pickman in my

571
00:34:49.257 --> 00:34:52.708
lab, and Yana now also has an independent lab at

572
00:34:52.747 --> 00:34:55.388
Dana-Farber focused on leukemia clinical genomics.

573
00:34:55.448 --> 00:34:58.848
And so together we formed the Pediatric LEAP

574
00:34:58.868 --> 00:35:01.708
Consortium, included 15 institutions.

575
00:35:02.197 --> 00:35:05.108
It was very generously supported by the St. Baldrick's Foundation.

576
00:35:05.148 --> 00:35:07.068
We could not have done this without their support.

577
00:35:07.788 --> 00:35:11.508
And we built this team of folks that worked incredibly well collaboratively

578
00:35:11.528 --> 00:35:15.388
together to bring in the early days of having clinical genomics

579
00:35:15.448 --> 00:35:18.978
tests to children with high-risk relapse

580
00:35:19.008 --> 00:35:22.948
refractory leukemia. And we greatly benefited from the pioneering work of

581
00:35:22.988 --> 00:35:26.138
Katie Janeway in getting this all off the ground.

582
00:35:26.948 --> 00:35:30.408
And so with this study, we asked a very simple question: Can we

583
00:35:30.468 --> 00:35:34.108
identify lesions that are immediately targetable with available drugs?

584
00:35:35.208 --> 00:35:38.888
And in some cases, the answer was yes, and this is just one example of a

585
00:35:38.908 --> 00:35:42.648
dramatic responder. This was a 10-year-old child who was diagnosed with

586
00:35:42.708 --> 00:35:46.448
B-ALL, and she got standard chemotherapy and then

587
00:35:46.928 --> 00:35:50.238
unfortunately relapsed. She had salvage chemo, she had a bone marrow

588
00:35:50.268 --> 00:35:52.328
transplant, and she had CAR T therapy.

589
00:35:52.348 --> 00:35:54.988
And with each of these, she had a relapse.

590
00:35:55.048 --> 00:35:58.628
And she came to our institute, she had genomic

591
00:35:58.648 --> 00:36:02.188
studies, and we found that she had an RCST1 ABL2

592
00:36:02.208 --> 00:36:06.078
fusion in her leukemia cells, and this was predicted to respond to

593
00:36:06.088 --> 00:36:09.948
imatinib. And so we were able to incorporate imatinib

594
00:36:10.028 --> 00:36:13.948
into a backbone regimen that she was actually not responding to the chemotherapy

595
00:36:13.988 --> 00:36:17.708
alone, but went into a complete remission. She had a transplant.

596
00:36:17.768 --> 00:36:21.508
She stayed on imatinib, and now many, many years later, she remains in a

597
00:36:21.568 --> 00:36:25.408
complete remission. So for this child, this type of clinical genomic study

598
00:36:25.448 --> 00:36:28.008
was critical to her long-term survival.

599
00:36:28.608 --> 00:36:32.468
But we know that these kinase fusions and kinase point mutations tend to

600
00:36:32.508 --> 00:36:36.348
be more rare in childhood cancers, and so we need to still tackle the

601
00:36:36.408 --> 00:36:40.220
harder challenges.And so one of the strategies that we have

602
00:36:40.260 --> 00:36:44.220
been exploring recently is an arm of the dependency map

603
00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:48.210
that I think is a little bit less well explored than the CRISPR arm, and

604
00:36:48.210 --> 00:36:51.020
that's the chemical screening arm of this work.

605
00:36:52.020 --> 00:36:55.700
Which uses prism screening, which was an approach established by

606
00:36:55.720 --> 00:36:59.140
Channing Yu in Todd Golub's lab, and then Steve Corsello did a lot of work to

607
00:36:59.160 --> 00:36:59.890
really bring this

608
00:37:00.920 --> 00:37:04.320
type of screening to bioactive and FDA-approved drug

609
00:37:04.400 --> 00:37:07.960
collections. And so what prism is, it's taking cancer cell

610
00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:11.860
lines, it's barcoding them, and then it's pooling them in collections of up

611
00:37:11.900 --> 00:37:15.660
to 25 models that have similar growth properties, and then screening

612
00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:19.500
them against decks of molecules. And so to date, in the order of

613
00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:23.300
800 plus cancer models have been screened against thousands of drugs.

614
00:37:25.020 --> 00:37:28.740
And so Toby Alloway, a very talented chemist who is learning

615
00:37:28.780 --> 00:37:32.760
chemical biology in our lab, asked a question in the way that we ask

616
00:37:32.800 --> 00:37:36.740
the CRISPR data. Are there molecules that are more active in Ewing

617
00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:39.860
than in all the other cancer models that have been screened?

618
00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:43.690
And what Toby found is that this molecule, R112, is

619
00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:46.130
very highly active in Ewing compared to everything else.

620
00:37:46.880 --> 00:37:50.840
And ironically, this was reported as a spleen tyrosine kinase inhibitor target

621
00:37:50.900 --> 00:37:54.740
I had worked on in AML. But in Ewing sarcoma, this is absolutely not the

622
00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:57.980
target. You can knock out SYK and the cells don't care.

623
00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:01.960
And in fact, all of the reported kinases that are targets of this molecule, none

624
00:38:02.020 --> 00:38:04.000
of them are relevant in Ewing sarcoma.

625
00:38:05.720 --> 00:38:09.600
So Toby went on, and he validated this finding, though, that the Ewing

626
00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:11.720
sarcoma models are very responsive.

627
00:38:11.880 --> 00:38:15.760
Other sarcomas that are non-Ewing are not responsive, and Ewing is really the most

628
00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:17.960
responsive of all of the models that were screened.

629
00:38:19.610 --> 00:38:23.560
And so to try to identify the targets, what he did here is he used

630
00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:27.580
a CRISPR rescue screening strategy where he used

631
00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:31.200
CRISPR to knock out each gene in the genome and then said, "Loss of what genes

632
00:38:31.300 --> 00:38:33.000
rescues the effects of this molecule?"

633
00:38:33.860 --> 00:38:37.620
And what he found is that there's incredibly strong reliance on

634
00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:41.240
UDP glucose metabolism for the activity of this molecule.

635
00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:44.780
And in particular, we showed that the knockout of

636
00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:47.599
UGT3A2 fully rescues the effect of the compound.

637
00:38:47.629 --> 00:38:49.960
And so this is essential to the activity.

638
00:38:50.180 --> 00:38:53.720
And while we don't have all the answers yet, what I thought was really exciting is

639
00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:56.920
UGT3A2 is wildly overexpressed in Ewing.

640
00:38:57.460 --> 00:38:59.100
It's a direct target of the fusion.

641
00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:03.540
It's not expressed in most cancers, and it's not expressed in most normal cells.

642
00:39:03.700 --> 00:39:05.740
So we think a really interesting mechanism.

643
00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:10.000
I think the target's a bystander of the

644
00:39:10.040 --> 00:39:13.880
fusion, but it's rendering exquisite response to the molecule, and we're still

645
00:39:13.980 --> 00:39:17.700
trying to figure out the actual details of mechanistically at a more

646
00:39:17.720 --> 00:39:19.320
granular level, how does this work.

647
00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:25.340
So in the last two minutes, I just want to mention a few thoughts on the

648
00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:27.860
therapeutic targeting of the actual fusion.

649
00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:32.210
And so we and many people are excited about the idea of using

650
00:39:32.260 --> 00:39:35.280
targeted protein degradation. There have been a number of exciting talks at the

651
00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:39.280
meeting about this topic. There are two primary flavors of this.

652
00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:42.940
One is bifunctional degraders, also called PROTACs or proteolysis

653
00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:46.940
targeting chimeras, where you have a ligand to your protein, a linker, and

654
00:39:46.980 --> 00:39:48.540
a ligand to an E3 ligase.

655
00:39:49.380 --> 00:39:52.580
Importantly, you still need a ligand to your protein of interest, so it's not like

656
00:39:52.640 --> 00:39:55.560
a 100% solution. You still have to find that.

657
00:39:56.300 --> 00:39:58.880
But there are a number of molecules that are in the clinic now.

658
00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:02.740
Two, just to name AR and ER PROTACs.

659
00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:06.320
They've been active and safe and tolerated.

660
00:40:07.040 --> 00:40:10.030
The other type of degrader are molecular glue-like degraders.

661
00:40:10.060 --> 00:40:12.640
These are monovalent molecules that bind a target.

662
00:40:12.700 --> 00:40:15.900
They bind an E3 and bring them in proximity, leading to degradation.

663
00:40:16.460 --> 00:40:19.940
And thalidomide and lenalidomide are two examples of these types of molecules.

664
00:40:21.600 --> 00:40:25.480
So we've been taking a strategy with Eric Fisher's lab to develop

665
00:40:25.980 --> 00:40:29.540
EWS-FLI GFP reporter models that also express

666
00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:33.480
mCherry to adapt this to high-throughput screening and then to screen in

667
00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:37.340
the order of over 100,000 molecules for molecules that by

668
00:40:37.420 --> 00:40:40.440
image-based readouts lead to loss of the fusion protein.

669
00:40:41.190 --> 00:40:45.169
And so we've put the first series of hits through a number of different assays, and

670
00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:48.640
we have several molecules that are still holding up across the assays.

671
00:40:48.780 --> 00:40:52.600
I'm just showing you, and I'll just describe this one here, where we see a

672
00:40:52.620 --> 00:40:56.440
really nice dose-responsive effect now in Ewing cells on the fusion.

673
00:40:56.940 --> 00:41:00.900
We see loss of NKX2.2 in a dose-responsive way, the direct target of the

674
00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:04.860
fusion. And this effect on viability as well as on GFP

675
00:41:04.880 --> 00:41:08.860
and mCherry can be rescued with a proteasome inhibitor, suggesting that the

676
00:41:08.900 --> 00:41:11.760
mechanism is likely vis-a-vis degradation.

677
00:41:11.900 --> 00:41:14.260
So a lot more work to do, but I think encouraging.

678
00:41:16.080 --> 00:41:19.900
And in the last few minutes, I just want to talk about another avenue that we're

679
00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:23.830
excited about. And I was really excited to see a number of talks at this

680
00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:27.370
meeting on this idea of using bifunctional

681
00:41:27.460 --> 00:41:29.660
molecules in new and interesting ways.

682
00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:33.589
And so this was a paper that was published by Nat Gray and

683
00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:37.300
Jerry Crabtree's lab that asked the question: Could you rewire

684
00:41:37.420 --> 00:41:40.780
cancer drivers to activate apoptotic cell death?

685
00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:44.700
And so here what they did is they took a bifunctional molecule that

686
00:41:44.740 --> 00:41:48.500
has a ligand for BRD4, has a linker and a ligand for

687
00:41:48.540 --> 00:41:51.580
BCL6. And they asked could they bring

688
00:41:51.600 --> 00:41:55.380
BRD4 to BCL6, and could they now turn

689
00:41:55.480 --> 00:41:58.780
on BCL6 repressed targets and induce cell death.

690
00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:03.140
And so they were able to show that indeed they can turn on BCL6 repressed

691
00:42:03.180 --> 00:42:06.580
targets in contexts such as lymphoma and induce cell death.

692
00:42:08.700 --> 00:42:12.589
So we were part of a U54 consortium where

693
00:42:12.640 --> 00:42:16.230
Nat Gray was engaged in this work with Jerry Crabtree's lab, and we started talking

694
00:42:16.320 --> 00:42:19.340
about could we do just a proof of concept study in Ewing.

695
00:42:19.380 --> 00:42:22.980
This is not a therapy. It's just proof of concept to ask the

696
00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:26.350
question: Can we start moving EWS-FLI around on

697
00:42:26.380 --> 00:42:28.830
chromatin using bifunctional chemistry?

698
00:42:28.970 --> 00:42:32.960
And so this work was led by Mike Bond, another chemist who is

699
00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:36.670
training in my lab, as well as a terrific team, Julia DiGiovanni and

700
00:42:36.780 --> 00:42:38.560
Brianna Howard. Julia is a data scientist.

701
00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:42.564
Brianna was a Harvard undergrad.And so we said, we don't have a

702
00:42:42.584 --> 00:42:46.564
great ligand for EWS-FLI, so we're going to engineer cells

703
00:42:46.624 --> 00:42:49.724
to express the fusion with an FKBP

704
00:42:49.964 --> 00:42:53.924
mutant. And then what we did is we used bifunctional molecules

705
00:42:53.984 --> 00:42:57.864
that had a ligand for the FKBP mutant, a linker, and a

706
00:42:57.904 --> 00:42:59.204
ligand for BCL6.

707
00:43:00.044 --> 00:43:03.804
And we said, can we now drag EWS-FLI to BCL6 repressed

708
00:43:03.884 --> 00:43:07.364
genes in Ewing? We don't think BCL6 is a great target for Ewing.

709
00:43:07.404 --> 00:43:09.344
This was just merely proof of concept.

710
00:43:10.484 --> 00:43:14.464
There was a EbtSIH is the active compound, lots of controls that I'm not going

711
00:43:14.484 --> 00:43:15.884
to talk about in the interest of time.

712
00:43:16.964 --> 00:43:19.324
So we defined BCL6 repressed genes.

713
00:43:20.004 --> 00:43:22.084
One I'm going to just show you some data on was SOX2.

714
00:43:22.604 --> 00:43:24.554
I didn't think this would work, but it actually did.

715
00:43:24.854 --> 00:43:28.664
I was very pleasantly surprised. So this is just showing the SOX2

716
00:43:28.684 --> 00:43:32.324
locus. When we treat with the bifunctional molecule, we

717
00:43:32.384 --> 00:43:36.264
gain E-FLI on chromatin pretty specifically.

718
00:43:36.304 --> 00:43:40.064
We see really nice opening of chromatin by ATAC-seq, and we

719
00:43:40.104 --> 00:43:43.284
see a gain in gene expression of SOX2.

720
00:43:43.324 --> 00:43:46.144
We see the same for CISH and a number of other targets.

721
00:43:46.204 --> 00:43:48.484
So I think in principle, this could work.

722
00:43:48.604 --> 00:43:52.164
There are many applications now for bifunctional molecules. This is just one.

723
00:43:52.544 --> 00:43:56.064
But I think this is a pretty exciting area for pediatric oncology.

724
00:43:57.664 --> 00:44:00.544
So this is kind of where we are now. This is what our lab does.

725
00:44:00.584 --> 00:44:03.854
We work on fusion oncoprotein biology, discovery of novel targets and

726
00:44:03.904 --> 00:44:07.784
molecules, mechanisms of response and resistance across a number of

727
00:44:07.824 --> 00:44:11.184
childhood cancers, and trying to stay nimble as new technologies

728
00:44:11.344 --> 00:44:11.844
evolve.

729
00:44:12.964 --> 00:44:15.944
Just some final comments. We've learned a ton over the years.

730
00:44:16.444 --> 00:44:19.384
We know these are cancers that have gone awry

731
00:44:19.394 --> 00:44:22.884
developmentally. They often retain dependency on these key

732
00:44:22.924 --> 00:44:25.944
lineage core regulatory circuit transcription factors.

733
00:44:26.404 --> 00:44:29.604
Cell state plasticity really is important in response to therapies.

734
00:44:30.144 --> 00:44:33.084
Typically, childhood cancers have few recurrent point mutations.

735
00:44:33.484 --> 00:44:35.154
Fusion oncoproteins are really common.

736
00:44:36.104 --> 00:44:39.844
EWS-FLI and other oncogenes, I do think, have a strong Goldilocks

737
00:44:39.864 --> 00:44:43.404
phenomena that we might be able to leverage through an activation lethality

738
00:44:43.504 --> 00:44:47.404
mechanism. And I think there are a lot of exciting opportunities now in

739
00:44:47.424 --> 00:44:51.184
therapy, from exploiting paralogs and developmentally restricted

740
00:44:51.194 --> 00:44:54.984
targets to leveraging this new degrader technology and other bifunctional

741
00:44:55.004 --> 00:44:55.564
molecules.

742
00:44:57.444 --> 00:44:59.644
I want to just end by thanking my lab.

